snippet.textDisplay: I'm no expert so take this comment with a grain of salt, but the comment about the hydrogen train was very misinformed, maybe it was a joke, but what he says is actually not as concerning as you would think, and i'm going to really simplify things to show you why, because, just think for a second, almost everyone in rich countries have a 2 ton piece of metal with a high volatile liquid inside of them, and it can potentially explode with every crash and even after the crash because gasoline is a liquid and it vaporizes slowly creating a total recipe for disaster if any flame is exposed in a large amount of time, but we use it on our cars everyday, and we are mostly good, because the risk is not that high at low speeds, when you go really fast there could be a problem, but i'm not here to talk about that, now let's compare that to a similar product like hydrogen tanks on cars on an accident like that, a usual tank with pressurized hydrogen can go up to 10,000 psi, normal atmospheric pressure is 14 psi or 1 bar, this means that a tank like that would have 689 bar, 689 times the atmospheric pressure which is a lot, that means that when punctured it will instantaneously dissipate in the air, a hydrogen filled balloon will rise up at 20 m/s and without balloon is a tiny fraction faster and that means that within seconds of a crash and if the tank punctures it will release the high pressure hydrogen into the air and it will rise more safely to the atmosphere than in comparison to other fuels available like liquid diesel or gasoline, if it's more safe then why the Hindenburg exploded like that? because they enclosed the hydrogen at atmospheric pressure and then it ignited, in an enclosed place with a puncture and at atmospheric pressure it doesn't have time to dissipate and because the Hindenburg was huge and in the air that hydrogen cannot be released because everyone will die, you have no other option but to see the hydrogen ignite because your "tank" is filled with an absurd amount of hydrogen at atmospheric pressure, they key argument being that it was ignited after the puncture and slowly got on fire, that cannot happen in more modern times where we don't depend on the flying properties of the hydrogen, but on the electric capabilities of the hydrogen fuel cells, so no, you aren't going to die on a hydrogen powered train, because it just doesn't make any sense, if any train goes off track you should be worried about that and not about the hydrogen, in fact, hydrogen fuel cells are more safe even if they ignite easier than gasoline or diesel.

snippet.textDisplay: This is bullsh*t; as a miner myself, I don't believe it. Has anyone done the math?  RTX3090 does like 120m/h for ETH, one of the most popular and most profitable GPU coins and costs $1500 USD (and uses ~300w) An Rx570 does 30MH for $100 USD and uses 100w. Four 570s required to get same hash rate as a 3090; costs less than 1/3 AND is 3/4 as efficient; Yes, the 3090 is more power efficient BUT costs $1100 more. You can ROI 4x3090s in about 100 days as compared to over 325 days for 3090. Combine that with the fact that last few gen AMD GPUs spank NV in mining..for example my RTX2060 pulls 32MH and cost me $500 CAD; rx570s cost me $105 CAD and do 32MH. I could believe AMD GPUs being bought up for mining. I do know SOME miners that got 3090s but most got ONE if they were lucky and more for experimentation to see what it can do than to actually buy it to use and ROI off of.

snippet.textDisplay: LOL  Not to ruin a Linus rant, but the hydrogen train story is safer than you allude to there.  Hydrogen, being the lightest element, rises rapidly and therefore burns straight up.  It doesn't really explode or fireball.  The Hindenburg fire was bad not because of the hydrogen, but because of the materials used to construct the Zeppelin.  Cars and trains running on hydrogen are safer than gas and diesel vehicles.  And while most vehicles don't benefit much from our lack of a hydrogen economy, the few cases where they do make sense are mass transit such as  buses and trains because they run nonstop and they fuel at controlled depots.  We need more clean fuel use in the world.  So please don't spread misinformation and FUD.

snippet.textDisplay:
Hydrogen is pretty often not very green. Yes burning Hydrogen creates no emissions but it has to be sourced and typically most of the worlds supply comes from processing crude oil. Where it is produced from electrolysis the energy to do so comes mainly from fossil fuels, as it is a surplus requirement, and either uses fossil energy directly or reduces the amount of green energy to be used elsewhere. Ironically it might actually end up being a polluter as the process to refine, store, and deliver it isn't very efficient and might actually mean it is creating more pollution overall than using fossil fuels directly.

About the only way it can be truly green is from a solar/wind farm that is built and designed from the ground up just to produce hydrogen. Until that becomes the norm it is a marketing exercise to dumbfound the naive into supporting a product as green when it probably really isn't.
